    Jamestown's first years were brutal. By January 1608 only 38 of the original 104 colonists were alive. A combination of dysentery, malaria, a burned fort, and an especially harsh winter had taken a heavy toll. Relief seemed impossible until more ships arrived in 1608 with supplies and – later – more gunpowder. Even so, the colonists lived in a deer fence fort and quarreled about leadership. The Virginia Company in London demanded quick profits, not realizing their laborers were just trying to survive. In Jamestown, the idealism of gentlemen investors clashed with the reality of hungry settlers.
  </p>

