    Legend has it that Pocahontas – Powhatan's daughter – dramatically saved Captain John Smith from ritual execution. According to Smith's own account, just as he was about to be clubbed to death, 11-year-old Pocahontas threw herself on him. Modern historians debate the true intent (some say it was a sacred ritual, not an attempted murder). Either way, after that tense encounter Smith and Chief Powhatan reached a shaky peace. Pocahontas (real name Mataoka) even learned English, was baptized “Rebecca,” and eventually married John Rolfe. (This Anglo-Indian marriage in 1614 helped end the First Anglo-Powhatan War.)
  </p>

