  <h2>The Starving Time (Winter 1609–1610)</h2>

  <p>
    Even peace with Powhatan didn't make life easy. In summer 1609, 600 new settlers arrived – the colony's population doubled. But fate was cruel: those ships ran aground in Bermuda, leaving Jamestown with <em>more mouths to feed and fewer supplies</em>. Chief Powhatan laid siege to the fort that winter, barring the English from hunting or raiding nearby farms. By late 1609 the settlers were desperate. Horses, dogs, cats, and rats were slaughtered for food, and the colonists even ate shoe leather. Archaeological and written evidence confirms that some resorted to cannibalism. As young George Percy, a colonist who survived to tell the tale, wrote later: <strong>“some ate their comrades and others <em>licked up the blood</em> which hath fallen from their weak fellows.”</strong>
  </p>

  <blockquote class="callout">
    “Some [colonists] ate their comrades and others ‘licked upp the Bloode which hath fallen from their weake fellowes.’”
  </blockquote>

  <p>
    By spring 1610 nearly the entire colony was gone – only about 60 of the 500+ original settlers remained alive. When Lord Delaware's relief fleet finally turned around (tipped off by burning tobacco), the survivors were ready to abandon Jamestown. It was <em>only</em> by the literal last minute that they turned their ships back, after the arrival of new colonists and provisions from Bermuda. The Virginia Company in London got the bad news: “Only sixty of the earlier 214 survived” – a financial catastrophe they could never have advertised in their investment prospectuses. Needless to say, many British investors wavered on their shares when they heard of Jamestown's starvation and chaos.
  </p>

  <h2>Anglo-Powhatan Wars</h2>

  <p>
    Relations with Chief Powhatan's confederacy took a permanent turn for the worse after the Starving Time. Early on, Governor Sir Thomas Gates and Thomas West, Lord De La Warr, decided on a strategy of conquest and holy conversion. The Company's instructions were blunt: if persuasion failed, it was “not cruelty nor a breach of charity to deal more sharply” with the Powhatans. In practice this led to brutal skirmishes and massacres. For example, in 1610 George Percy (now governor) led an attack that destroyed the Paspahegh village; according to a period chronicle, Percy later “put [a captured] queen to the sworde” and even threw captured children overboard, shooting them in the river. (This savagery horrified some Jamestowners – evidently Percy himself had “seene so mutch bloodshedd that day” that he spared the Paspahegh queen from being burned alive – but the damage was done.)
  </p>

  <blockquote class="callout">
    “In 1610, with 60 men, Percy's force 'put [a captured] Queen to the sworde' and 'put her children to death by throwing them overboard and shooting out their braines in the water.'”
  </blockquote>
  
 

  <p>
    Meanwhile, English colonists built forts up and down the river to defend themselves, and took native cornfields by force when needed. Hostilities quieted a bit during Rolfe and Pocahontas's marriage peace, but after Powhatan died in 1618 his brother <strong>Opechancanough</strong> became paramount chief and war party. In 1622 he organized a surprise assault on Good Friday: Powhatan warriors across the James Valley coordinated to attack plantations and villages. About 350 colonists – roughly a quarter of Virginia's English population – were slaughtered that day. Jamestown itself was largely spared, but the colony was shaken to its core.
  </p>
