  <p>
    The colonial response was merciless. They declared a war of extermination: English militias laid waste to Native towns wherever they found them. Over the next decade, the conflict ebbed and flowed. A Third Anglo-Powhatan War (1644–46) led by an aging Opechancanough nearly wiped out the English again before a peace treaty was signed. In each war, the balance tipped slightly in England's favor only as more settlers flooded Virginia and gained firepower. By 1646 Powhatan rule had collapsed – but the price was enormous suffering on both sides.
  </p>

  <h2>Spanish Spies and Other Threats</h2>

  <p>
    Jamestown was not just beset by Native wars. Spain, claiming all of the Americas, regarded an English foothold as a strategic threat. Until 1604 England and Spain were officially at peace, but wary spies lurked. In 1611 a Spanish galleon anchored near Point Comfort, and two men – captain Diego de Molina and an aide – came ashore only to be seized by the fort's garrison. Governor Thomas Dale suspected a scouting mission for a Spanish invasion. He later fretted, <em>“What may be the danger of this unto us who are here so few, so weake and unfortified?”</em> (England and Spain had only narrowly signed the Treaty of London in 1604.)
  </p>

  <blockquote class="callout">
    “Governor Thomas Dale worried: 'What may be the danger of this unto us who are here so few, so weake and unfortified?'”
  </blockquote>

  <p>
    Fortunately for the colonists, no Spanish armada materialized at Jamestown. Still, the English kept one eye on the sea. Plans were even made to move the colony upriver (to “Henricus”) to frustrate any naval attack. Ultimately, the bigger threats remained hunger and hostile Indians. And of course the infighting back in London: the Virginia Company's charter was revoked in 1624 after the 1622 massacre shook royal confidence. Virginia became a crown colony, but the same dramas of power and prejudice would follow – through Bacon's Rebellion (1676) and beyond.
  </p>

